## Capturing screenshots

**Use a real desktop browser (Chrome, Safari, Arc) for the actual capture.**
The `cursor-ide-browser` MCP webview is constrained to roughly `1024 px`
wide regardless of `browser_resize`, which puts the Cube app into its
narrow-viewport layout (hamburger menu, compact dashboard cards, "best on
a wider screen" warning). Don't ship those as docs screenshots — they
don't reflect what users see.

The MCP browser is still useful for:

- Navigating to and logging into the demo account.
- Setting up state (selecting a chart type, opening a panel) before you
  switch to a real browser to capture.
- Quick verification screenshots when you're iterating on a description
  and don't intend to ship the image.

For the real capture, follow this flow:

1. Open the demo deployment in Chrome/Safari at the size you want.
2. Set the state you want to document.
3. Use the OS screenshot tool (`Cmd+Shift+4` on macOS for a region,
   `Cmd+Shift+5` for a window) or DevTools' "Capture screenshot" command
   in the device toolbar.
4. Save as PNG, then drop into the upload script.

Steps for any capture, real-browser or MCP:

1. **Set the viewport** to a consistent size before capturing:
   - **Default:** `1440 × 900` for full-app screenshots (matches a typical
     MacBook/laptop and is what existing screenshots use).
   - **Inline / partial UI** (e.g. a single dropdown, a panel): capture at
     `1440 × 900` and crop to the relevant area afterward — don't shrink
     the viewport, it changes the layout.
   - **Mobile** (rare, only when the doc is specifically about mobile):
     `390 × 844`.
2. **Theme:** match the surrounding section. Default to **light theme**
   unless the page is specifically about a dark-mode feature. If a single
   page compares both themes, capture two images and label them
   `-light` / `-dark`.
3. **State:** make sure the screenshot reflects the documented behavior —
   the right tab open, the right chart type selected, the right filter
   applied. Hide unrelated banners (notifications, "what's new" popovers,
   trial-status bars) before capturing.
4. **Hide identifying info:** the demo account shouldn't show your name or
   real email; if it does (avatar in the top-right, "Welcome, ..."), crop
   it out.
5. **Format:**
   - PNG for UI screenshots.
   - WebP if the PNG is >300 KB after compression.
   - SVG only for diagrams you authored, never for screenshots.
6. **Compress** before uploading. The bucket is cached forever, so a 2 MB
   screenshot stays 2 MB forever. Run through `pngquant`, `oxipng`, or
   `cwebp` before you upload.

When the user asks for a screenshot of a feature that's only behind a flag
or gated by a plan, check `~/code/cubejs-enterprise` for whether the demo
account has access — don't fake the UI.

## Naming and uploading

Follow the path conventions in `static-assets.mdc`. For docs screenshots
that means:

```
docs/<section>/<page-slug>/<descriptor>.png
```

Where:

- `<section>` mirrors the docs folder (`explore-analyze`, `data-modeling`,
  `admin`, etc.).
- `<page-slug>` mirrors the `.mdx` filename without extension.
- `<descriptor>` is a short kebab-case description of what the image shows.

Examples:

```bash
./scripts/upload-asset.sh ./bar-stacked.png \
  docs/explore-analyze/charts/chart-types/bar-stacked.png

./scripts/upload-asset.sh ./series-config-panel.png \
  docs/explore-analyze/charts/configuration/series-configuration-panel.png

./scripts/upload-asset.sh ./entra-saml-app.png \
  admin/sso/microsoft-entra-id/saml-application.png
```

Run the script from `docs-mintlify/`. It prints the
`https://static.cube.dev/<key>` URL.

If you need light + dark variants, suffix with `-light` / `-dark`:
`bar-stacked-light.png` and `bar-stacked-dark.png`.

## Embedding in MDX

Always wrap screenshots in `<Frame>` so Mintlify renders the standard
border, shadow, and lightbox affordances. Include an `alt` description for
accessibility:

```mdx
<Frame>
  <img
    src="https://static.cube.dev/docs/explore-analyze/charts/chart-types/bar-stacked.png"
    alt="Stacked bar chart showing revenue by product category, stacked by order status"
  />
</Frame>
```

For a caption, use Mintlify's `caption` prop on `<Frame>`:

```mdx
<Frame caption="Stacked bar chart — revenue by product category, stacked by order status">
  <img src="https://static.cube.dev/docs/explore-analyze/charts/chart-types/bar-stacked.png" />
</Frame>
```

For a theme-aware pair (light/dark), use Mintlify's built-in light/dark
image swap:

```mdx
<Frame>
  <img className="block dark:hidden" src="https://static.cube.dev/.../bar-light.png" />
  <img className="hidden dark:block" src="https://static.cube.dev/.../bar-dark.png" />
</Frame>
```

When you replace a `{/* Screenshot: ... */}` placeholder, drop the entire
comment — don't leave it next to the embed.

## Updating an existing screenshot

Asset URLs are immutable (see `static-assets.mdc`). To refresh a screenshot:

1. Capture the new version.
2. Upload under a versioned key: `bar-stacked-v2.png`.
3. Update the `<img src>` in the same PR.

Never `--force` overwrite a live image — the CDN will keep serving the
cached copy and the docs will look broken/stale to anyone who cached it.

## Don't

- Don't screenshot real customer deployments or production accounts. Use
  the demo account above.
- Don't commit `.png`/`.jpg` screenshots into `docs-mintlify/` itself —
  they go to S3 (see `static-assets.mdc`).
- Don't reference Contentful URLs (`ucarecdn.com`, `images.ctfassets.net`)
  in new screenshots. Existing references are being migrated; if you touch
  one, mirror it to `static.cube.dev` while you're there.
- Don't paste screenshots that include another tab's content, your OS
  menu bar, browser dev tools, or notification overlays.
- Don't crop so tightly that the screenshot loses context (a button is
  fine; a button with no surrounding panel is confusing).
